[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]Renfrewshire Council [bold]1.1.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Renfrewshire Council continues to express concerns that the reforms to support for 
[normal]              
[normal]housing costs being considered by this inquiry will exacerbate poverty for the most 
[normal]              
[normal]vulnerable individuals and families. 
[normal]1.2.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]The Renfrewshire area includes the Ferguslie area of Paisley, the single most deprived 
[normal]              
[normal]datazone in Scotland (see the Ren
[normal]frewshire c
[normal]ontext - Appendix 1
[normal], A). This area and 
[normal]              
[normal]other more vulnerable communities in Renfrewshire already face significant challenges 
[normal]              
[normal]and the measures being introduced by the UK Government will lead to increased 
[normal]              
[normal]financial stress for households and create additio
[normal]nal service pressures arising from 
[normal]              
[normal]demand for welfare, debt and money advice, additional family distress and increased 
[normal]              
[normal]homelessness presentations.
[normal]1.3.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]From the Council’s perspective there are clear financial risks relating to the 
[normal]              
[normal]management and sustainabil
[normal]ity of the Housing Revenue Account (HRA). These are 
[normal]              
[normal]linked to increases in rent collection costs and bad debts associated with an increasing 
[normal]              
[normal]requirement to collect rent as a result of reducing benefit levels available to tenants and 
[normal]              
[normal]proposals for housin
[normal]g benefit payments to be made directly to the claimant under the 
[normal]              
[normal]proposed Universal Credit system.
[normal]1.4.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Additionally, the Council is concerned that the make up and availability of housing stock 
[normal]              
[normal]at local authority level does not appear to have been taken into
[normal] account when 
[normal]              
[normal]introducing the under 
[normal]occupancy reduction. (Appendix 1
[normal], B) refers. This places 
[normal]              
[normal]significant challenges for social landlords, including Renfrewshire Council where there 
[normal]              
[normal]is a mismatch between the housing requirements of tenants affected by th
[normal]e under 
[normal]              
[normal]occupancy reduction and the benefit cap and the availability of suitably sized stock. 
[normal]1.5.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Renfrewshire Council anticipates a number of potential impacts on its statutory duty in 
[normal]              
[normal]relation to homelessness as a result of the Housing Benefit changes. I
[normal]n particular, the 
[normal]              
[normal]application of the under occupancy reduction to local authority owned stock used to 
[normal]              
[normal]temporarily accommodate people presenting as homeless, while exempting other 
[normal]              
[normal]tenures of property used, does not recognise the effective use that is mad
[normal]e of LA 
[normal]              
[normal]owned accommodation to meet such emergency accommodation needs.  The loss of 
[normal]              
[normal]housing benefit and the resulting increase in rent arrears may ultimately lead to 
[normal]              
[normal]increased housing benefit costs as the council may be forced to consider greater use o
[normal]f 
[normal]              
[normal]the private sector provision, where rent levels may prove to be higher, in order to meet 
[normal]              
[normal]its statutory duties in relation to homelessness and protect against financial loss to the 
[normal]              
[normal]Council. 
[normal]1.6.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]The proposed introduction of direct payment of housing costs
[normal] within Universal Credit is 
[normal]              
[normal]expected to lead to greater financial stress for households and individuals and will place 
[normal]              
[normal]extreme financial pressures on the long term sustainability of social housing where 
[normal]              
[normal]households are unable to budget appropriately and 
[normal]manage the ongoing responsibility 
[normal]              
[normal]of sustaining their rent payments.
[normal]2.1.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Renfrewshire Council has deployed significant additional r
[normal]esources of £1.3 million in 
[normal]              
[normal]2013/14 and beyond to provide the Council with the best opportunity to prepare for and 
[normal]              
[normal]manage the anticipated increase in demand for services. Much of this investment is 
[normal]              
[normal]directed towards advice and support to ensure the Counc
[normal]il is well placed to both 
[normal]              
[normal]support the tenants and their families manage the impact of welfare change, but also to 
[normal]              
[normal]seek to pro-actively protect the financial position of the Council’s housing function, in 
[normal]              
[normal]particular the sustainability of its rental strea
[normal]m during this transition.
[normal]2.2.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Renfrewshire Council has formally recognised that where tenants subject to the under 
[normal]              
[normal]occupancy reduction are actively engaged with the Council and are taking reasonable 
[normal]              
[normal]steps to maintain a rent repayment arrangement the council
[normal] will continue to pursue rent 
[normal]              
[normal]due without resorting to eviction. However, it needs to be recognised that increasing 
[normal]              
[normal]rental arrears ultimately places significant financial pressures on the Council’s Housing 
[normal]              
[normal]Revenue Account which will in turn increase the
[normal] associated future rental costs for social 
[normal]              
[normal]housing within Renfrewshire. 
[normal]2.3.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]In recognition of this, the Council has in addition,  agreed to set aside £850,000 from 
[normal]              
[normal]the Housing Revenue Account (HRA) for 2013/14 to help mitigate the impacts of 
[normal]              
[normal]welfare refor
[normal]m on Council tenants, part of which will be targeted at providing a scheme 
[normal]              
[normal]of financial support for tenants experiencing hardship. Given the close links with the 
[normal]              
[normal]Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) Discretionary Housing Payment (DHP) 
[normal]              
[normal]scheme, options 
[normal]for criteria for the HRA financial hardship support scheme are being 
[normal]              
[normal]developed taking account of the circumstances and outcomes of applications made by 
[normal]              
[normal]tenants for DHP. However, it is recognised that both schemes will provide only 
[normal]              
[normal]temporary support and 
[normal]relief for affected tenants.
[normal]2.4.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]In addition, Renfrewshire Council has increased its top up funding to DHP resources by 
[normal]              
[normal]150% by allocating an additional £150,000 to the DHP fund for 2013/14 in recognition 
[normal]              
[normal]that the DWP resources are insufficient to provide t
[normal]he necessary short term support to 
[normal]              
[normal]affected citizens across Renfrewshire. The Council administration is proposing to 
[normal]              
[normal]further enhance the fund up to the maximum allowable at the C
[normal]ouncil meeting 
[normal]              
[normal]scheduled for 3
[normal] October 2013. The enhanced fund will help de
[normal]fray the loss of 
[normal]              
[normal]Housing Benefit and provide tenants with short term support that will allow them to 
[normal]              
[normal]meet their rent obligations while considering other options.
[normal]2.5.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]The integration of housing officers to neighbourhood area housing teams has also been 
[normal]              
[normal]take
[normal]n forward by the Council in order to support ongoing tenancy management 
[normal]              
[normal]activities. Officers continue to take proactive measures to support tenants affected and 
[normal]              
[normal]we have increased the number of officers available to offer advice and assistance, 
[normal]              
[normal]including
[normal] specialist money advice to make sure that tenants have access to good 
[normal]              
[normal]advice and support.  This includes maximising any opportunity to access benefit 
[normal]              
[normal]entitlement, support access to any possible financial support funds in place, and also 
[normal]              
[normal]covers repaymen
[normal]t planning and referral to training and employment services. 
