[normal]with the team focusing on a wider group of council tenants and their households.  The 
[normal]              
[normal]first programme resulted in all but o
[normal]ne of the young participants progressing to 
[normal]              
[normal]employment or further education.
[normal]2.8.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Housing options advice has been extended to include employment sign posting and 
[normal]              
[normal]relevant housing staff have been trained and plans are being progressed to deploy an 
[normal]              
[normal]employment
[normal] adviser dedicated to support unemployed tenants.  
[normal]3.1.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Both local authority and RSL housing stock is in significant demand as evidenced by 
[normal]              
[normal]the waiting lists, owner occupation is very diffi
[normal]cult to access at present due to high 
[normal]              
[normal]purchase prices, the requirement for large deposits and the lack of availability of 
[normal]              
[normal]mortgage finance. The Council is already aware that tenants impacted are Housing 
[normal]              
[normal]Benefit claimants and this is unlikely to be an op
[normal]tion available to them. 
[normal]3.2.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]In Renfrewshire a Housing Options approach is in place; as part of housing advice 
[normal]              
[normal]services, tenants and applicants are given an overview of all housing options available 
[normal]              
[normal]to them, including discussions around alternative tenures including the private rented 
[normal]              
[normal]sector.
[normal]3.3.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]The private rented sector is relatively smaller compared to other tenures and wider 
[normal]              
[normal]welfare reforms will also make this sector more difficult to access. Tenan
[normal]ts leaving their 
[normal]              
[normal]current homes may end up staying with family or friends or present as homeless putting 
[normal]              
[normal]greater pressure on existing services.
[normal]3.4.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Shelter Scotland, have indicated that people judged to be under-occupying in the social 
[normal]              
[normal]sector and who can't 
[normal]afford the shortfall, will be forced with the choice to downsize or 
[normal]              
[normal]run up arrears. Due to the widely recognised chronic shortage of one-bedroom social 
[normal]              
[normal]houses, the charity says many will have to turn to the private rented sector. In 
[normal]              
[normal]Renfrewshire the exi
[normal]stence of the required number of one bed room private rented 
[normal]              
[normal]properties is questionable.
[normal]3.5.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]As highlighted in tables 1 and 2 in Appendix 
[normal]1
[normal], rent for a one-bedroom property in the 
[normal]              
[normal]private sector is on average higher than rent for a two-bedroom social proper
[normal]ty. 
[normal]              
[normal]Tenants electing to transition to a private tenancy as means to alleviate the impact of 
[normal]              
[normal]under occupancy rules on a social tenancy, would qualify for full Local Housing 
[normal]              
[normal]Allowance (LHA) as they would no longer be assessed as under-occupying – 
[normal]              
[normal]pervers
[normal]ely this would be costing the public purse more in terms of providing housing 
[normal]              
[normal]costs support than it would to provide full benefit support for a social rented property 
[normal]              
[normal]without any associated under occupancy reduction.
[normal]Under occupancy reduction[bold]4.1.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]The removal of the spare room subsidy, or the bedroom tax, as it is more commonly 
[normal]              
[normal]known, has introduced deductions from housing benefit on tenants who are deemed to 
[normal]              
[normal]have more bedrooms than they need. As referred to ea
[normal]rlier, options for tenants in 
[normal]              
[normal]this situation are limited as the housing stock in the area does not match the associated 
[normal]              
[normal]demand for smaller one bedroom properties and with many affected tenants advising 
[normal]              
[normal]the Council that they  have no way of making up the
[normal] shortfall. 
[normal]4.2.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]At the point of implementation of the under occupancy reduction, a total of 1,960 
[normal]              
[normal]Council tenants lost £1.2 million a year in housing benefit (as detailed in table 3, 
[normal]              
[normal]Appendix 1
[normal]) and 1,100 Housing Association tenants lost £0.6 million a yea
[normal]r in housing 
[normal]              
[normal]benefit. It is anticipated that a major component of this loss in benefit will lead to a 
[normal]              
[normal]reduction in rental income for both the Council and Registered Social Landlords (RSLs). 
[normal]4.3.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Based on data from the end of July 2013, July the number of te
[normal]nants affected by Under 
[normal]              
[normal]Occupancy and in arrears has risen to 1,464, with only 27% of households affected 
[normal]              
[normal]maintaining a clear rent account. The increase in rent arrears since the start of the 
[normal]              
[normal]financial year and introduction of the under occupancy reduct
[normal]ion is £229,000. This is 
[normal]              
[normal]despite the proactive attempts of the Council to inform and support tenants through the 
[normal]              
[normal]changes and places significant financial risks on the potential to recover unpaid rent 
[normal]              
[normal]going forward.
[normal]4.4.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]The 2013/14 HRA Business Plan include
[normal]s an anticipated increase in the level of 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]budgeted bad debt provision from 2.5% to 3.5% (c£400k increase) and 5% (c£600k 
[normal]              
[normal]increase) thereafter. In addition, previously anticipated staffing savings of £300k in 
[normal]              
[normal]2015/16 and £200k in 2016/17 have been remov
[normal]ed from the HRA Business Plan to 
[normal]              
[normal]reflect the anticipation of increasing service pressures to support tenants and address 
[normal]              
[normal]growing rental arrears. In addition to this, further budgeted resources  of £331,000 per 
[normal]              
[normal]annum have also been built in for 2013/14 a
[normal]nd moving forward to provide the 
[normal]              
[normal]necessary staffing resources that are anticipated, as best can be at this point,  to be 
[normal]              
[normal]required to provide these additional services and manage the additional service 
[normal]              
[normal]pressures. Any increased costs or reduction in incom
[normal]e for 2014/15 to 2017/18 will be 
[normal]              
[normal]built into future Business Plans once increasing certainty is established over the 
[normal]              
[normal]emerging impact of the under occupancy reduction and the wider reform agenda. 
[normal]4.5.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Housing Benefit paid to tenants in the private rented sect
[normal]or is based on Local Housing 
[normal]              
[normal]Allowance (LHA) rates. The LHA rates in Renfrewshire are higher for all property sizes 
[normal]              
[normal]than in the social rented sector. As referred to above, it is anticipated that a counter-
[normal]              
[normal]productive consequence of the under occupancy ru
[normal]les will see some  tenants under 
[normal]              
[normal]occupying in the social sector, electing  to move to the private sector and receive an 
[normal]              
[normal]increased amount of housing benefit for a smaller sized property. 
[normal]4.6.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Renfrewshire Council also expects a number of possible impacts on 
[normal]homelessness 
[normal]              
[normal]generally which are anticipated to emerge as a direct result of the HB changes. These 
[normal]              
[normal]include pressure on the proportion of lets to homeless applicants due to an increase in 
[normal]              
[normal]transfer requests from existing tenants in receipt of housing bene
[normal]fit who are under-
[normal]              
[normal]occupying their homes - this may in turn lead to an increase in the length of time taken 
[normal]              
[normal]to complete the local authorities duty to house those who are unintentionally homeless, 
[normal]              
[normal]and an increase in the need to provide (and fund) temporar
[normal]y accommodation – it should 
[normal]              
[normal]be noted that even those who are deemed to be intentionally homeless can require to 
[normal]              
[normal]be provided with temporary accommodation.
[normal]4.7.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Renfrewshire Council has always recognised the housing circumstances of Council 
[normal]              
[normal]tenants and tenant
[normal]s seeking to transfer are given a proportion of available lets within 
[normal]              
[normal]the current allocation policy. 
[normal]The Council is continuing to take a flexible approach in 
[normal]              
[normal]consideration of mutual exchange applications to accommodate those tenants impacted 
[normal]              
[normal]by the unde
[normal]r-
[normal]              
