[normal]Benefit cap[bold]4.8.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]While numbers affected by the benefit cap within Renfrewshire are low (29), for the 
[normal]              
[normal]affected larger families this poses significant concern. The annual reduction in housing 
[normal]              
[normal]benefit paid to these households is currently estimated as £106,384. Input from DWP 
[normal]              
[normal]and other agencies, including the Council will be required to provide support to the 
[normal]              
[normal]families in relation to employability and housing options.
[normal]Support and Exempt accommo[bold]dation[bold]4.9.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Discussions have commenced with the Council’s commissioned housing support 
[normal]              
[normal]providers to look at current service specifications; current housing support provision; 
[normal]              
[normal]current housing management provision to determine what changes need to be 
[normal]              
[normal]consider
[normal]ed when developing new tenders for these commissioned services.  In the 
[normal]              
[normal]future housing support and housing management must be much more clearly aligned 
[normal]              
[normal]within service contracts to ensure supported accommodation projects are sustainable. 
[normal]              
[normal]While the DWP ha
[normal]s indicated that they wish to better understand the supported housing 
[normal]              
[normal]sector and the impact of housing benefit in the sector in order to protect existing 
[normal]              
[normal]provision from the unintended consequences of welfare reform, until this work is 
[normal]              
[normal]concluded risks re
[normal]main in relation to supported housing provision.
[normal]Temporary Accommodation[bold]4.10.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Under occupancy restrictions are being placed on HB recipients placed in Council 
[normal]              
[normal]owned temporary accommodation. This is not the case where tenants are placed in 
[normal]              
[normal]privately sourced/le
[normal]ased accommodation used for this purpose. In Renfrewshire 88% or 
[normal]              
[normal]147 out of 167 properties used to house people presenting as homeless are council 
[normal]              
[normal]owned therefore this potentially places an additional burden. The majority of 
[normal]              
[normal]households living in tempora
[normal]ry accommodation receive housing benefit and are placed 
[normal]              
[normal]in accommodation arising from an urgent need rather than a strict adherence to size 
[normal]              
[normal]criteria. By the end of July 2013 arrears of approximately £27,000 of under occupancy 
[normal]              
[normal]arrears had accumulated.
[normal]4.11.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Re
[normal]nfrewshire Council recognises its duty to minimise homelessness and protect the 
[normal]              
[normal]vulnerable. In the short term, the impact of the HB reduction will in effect create a 
[normal]              
[normal]benefit gap which is not being passed on to homeless people temporarily lodged in 
[normal]              
[normal]accom
[normal]modation. This is a new burden and a form of cost shunting from the DWP to 
[normal]              
[normal]local authorities which has the direct impact of diverting already stretched Council 
[normal]              
[normal]resources away from other priority areas in order for the Council to protect the most 
[normal]              
[normal]vulnera
[normal]ble of clients from what is seen as an unintended consequence of welfare 
[normal]              
[normal]changes. However, it is recognised that this action taken by the Council will not be 
[normal]              
[normal]sustainable in the long term and addressing this unintended and unfair consequence of 
[normal]              
[normal]the refor
[normal]ms on the most vulnerable of individuals is something which the Council 
[normal]              
[normal]continues to lobby the DWP for through a range of routes.
[normal]4.12.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In addition, it is intended that housing costs for short stay tenants will be included in 
[normal]              
[normal]Universal Credit at LHA rates and 
[normal]paid direct to tenants. There will also be a 
[normal]              
[normal]management element, or overhead, however the method to be applied has yet to be 
[normal]              
[normal]determined. The Council has significant concerns over the underlying logic of this 
[normal]              
[normal]approach which is expected to place significa
[normal]nt pressure on already extremely 
[normal]              
[normal]vulnerable clients and it is fully anticipated that a very high level of non payment of 
[normal]              
[normal]associated rent will occur as a consequence. An estimated non-recovery of £482,000 in 
[normal]              
[normal]annual rental income relating to the direct pa
[normal]yment of the Housing Benefit element to 
[normal]              
[normal]short stay tenants through Universal Credit is expected to have an impact on the 
[normal]              
[normal]Council’s ability to provide Short Stay, temporary accommodation.
[normal]4.13.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Work is ongoing to look at the current modelling of temporary and supported 
[normal]              
[normal]accommodation to determine the future viability of the current model of service delivery, 
[normal]              
[normal]which at present proves to be highly effective at meeting the immediate needs of 
[normal]              
[normal]vulner
[normal]able individuals and families. The Council is also looking at developing other 
[normal]              
[normal]options within the private sector to ensure single households have sustainable and 
[normal]              
[normal]affordable temporary housing options in accommodation that is the correct size and 
[normal]              
[normal]meets th
[normal]eir needs. The Council is currently carrying out scoping exercises of empty 
[normal]              
[normal]buildings and cost analysis on buildings that could potentially meet the Council’s 
[normal]              
[normal]requirements moving forward. However, it is recognised that such potential re-
[normal]              
[normal]modelling of ser
[normal]vice delivery comes with the risk that what is subsequently put in place 
[normal]              
[normal]fails to deliver an equivalent level of service, impacting once again on some of the most 
[normal]              
[normal]vulnerable in our society.
[normal]LHA changes [bold]4.14.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]During 2012/13 the Council supplemented the DHP fun
[normal]d by giving a total of £168,000 
[normal]              
[normal]and over the last year Renfrewshire Council actively supported private sector tenants 
[normal]              
[normal]impacted by the LHA changes. Tenants were contacted and invited to apply for a 
[normal]              
[normal]Discretionary Housing Payment as a means of providing sh
[normal]ort term support to allow 
[normal]              
[normal]them time to consider their options or seek alternative accommodation. Overall 
[normal]              
[normal]£104,000 was awarded to tenants in private rented accommodation with £26,000 of this 
[normal]              
[normal]arising from the direct contact made by council staff to tenant
[normal]s affected by the LHA 
[normal]              
[normal]changes. The Council continues to support these customers however with the scale of 
[normal]              
[normal]the changes for social sector tenants the DHP fund is expected to be under significant 
[normal]              
[normal]pressure as the year progresses therefore it is anticipated 
[normal]that there will be less scope 
[normal]              
[normal]to provide a similar level of assistance to affected tenants.
[normal]Changes to non dependant deductions[bold]4.15.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Council recognises that non dependent adults living in a property are expected to 
[normal]              
[normal]make a contribution to housing costs, ba
[normal]sed on income. The increase in non dependant 
[normal]              
[normal]deductions over the last two years places additional pressures on landlords in collecting 
[normal]              
[normal]the balance due from non dependants and with the introduction of the under occupancy 
[normal]              
[normal]means that the presence of a non 
[normal]dependant can lead to the need for detailed benefit 
[normal]              
[normal]advice. Households with non dependants have been beneficiaries of DHP payments 
[normal]              
[normal]over the last year.
[normal]5.1.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Discretionary Housing Payments (DHP) provide claimants with additional 
[normal]financial 
[normal]              
[normal]assistance with housing costs, in addition to any welfare benefits, where a local 
[normal]              
[normal]authority considers that further help is required. The DWP allocate the fund to councils 
[normal]              
[normal]and councils can, under the legislation, consider adding to this fund up
[normal] to a maximum of 
[normal]              
[normal]2.5 times the DWP allocation. In short to medium term a DHP award is likely to be one 
[normal]              
[normal]of a limited number of options open to support tenants.  
[normal]5.2.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]The UK Government increased the overall DHP fund to help mitigate some of the short 
[normal]              
[normal]to medi
[normal]um term impact of the Housing Benefit changes. The Renfrewshire allocation 
[normal]              
[normal]has increased from £74,464 in 2012/13 to £267,351 in 2013/14. The DWP has advised 
[normal]              
[normal]that this increased level of discretionary funding is to be targeted at mitigating the 
[normal]              
[normal]impact of
[normal] the under occupancy reduction, the benefit cap and the impact on temporary 
[normal]              
[normal]accommodation after the introduction of Universal Credit. 
[normal]5.3.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]In the last two financial years the Council has approved additional top up DHP funding 
[normal]              
[normal]of £60,000 in each year. The UK
[normal] Government allocations were £52,314 in 2011/12 and 
[normal]              
[normal]£74,464 for 2012/13. 
[normal]5.4.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]In addition to the DWP allocation for 2013/14 of £267,351 the Council has approved 
[normal]              
[normal]additional top up support for the DHP fund by £150,000 (150% of previous year) from 
[normal]              
[normal]its own res
[normal]ources bringing the total support available to £417,351 to provide tenants 
[normal]              
[normal]with short term support that will allow them to meet their rent obligations while 
[normal]              
[normal]considering other options. While the Council took this necessary step it is recognised 
[normal]              
[normal]that this
[normal] will not address the loss of benefit of £1.8 million across all housing providers 
[normal]              
[normal]in relation to the under occupancy alone. There is a proposal going to the Co
[normal]uncil 
[normal]              
[normal]meeting on 3
[normal] October 2013 to bring the Council’s contribution up to the maximum 
[normal]              
[normal]allowab
[normal]le.
[normal]5.5.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Data on DHP awards since April 2013 highlight that 85% of the awards are being made 
[normal]              
[normal]to tenants affected by the under occupancy reduction, with households unable to move 
[normal]              
[normal]for health reasons and families where an extra room is required for access to ch
[normal]ildren 
[normal]              
[normal]benefiting most.
[normal]6.1.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Renfrewshire Council would like to take the opportunity to draw the Work and Pensions 
[normal]              
[normal]Committee’s attention to another significantly concerning aspect of the UK Governmen
[normal]t 
[normal]              
[normal]welfare changes linked to the introduction of Universal Credit – direct payments. The 
[normal]              
[normal]Council view this proposal as the biggest single financial risk to the long term 
[normal]              
[normal]sustainability of housing services within Renfrewshire. It breaks the existing 
[normal]              
[normal]arra
[normal]ngement of housing benefit support being paid direct to the landlord and places 
[normal]              
[normal]responsibility on individual tenants to manage their overall finances and sustain on an 
[normal]              
[normal]ongoing basis payment of their rent. It is the Council’s view that although many tenan
[normal]ts 
[normal]              
[normal]will, with appropriate support from the Council, transition to this new arrangement, a 
[normal]              
[normal]large number will struggle which will inevitably lead to a significant increase in rent 
[normal]              
[normal]arrears, placing increased financial pressures on social landlords and long
[normal]er term rental 
[normal]              
[normal]levels. 
[normal]6.2.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Emerging findings from the DWP Demonstration projects highlights the increase in the 
[normal]              
[normal]level of non payment of rent and where rental income is being recovered, this is at a 
[normal]              
[normal]significant cost to the social landlords involved – a cos
[normal]t that DWP do not at this stage 
[normal]              
[normal]appear willing to support. Given the limitations of the demonstration projects concerns 
[normal]              
[normal]remain over the long term impact of direct payment and the cost of supporting tenants 
[normal]              
[normal]to make payment and the impact on household inc
[normal]omes and social landlord revenue 
[normal]              
[normal]streams where conflicts arise. Using Council data, if 10% of tenants do not pay rent the 
[normal]              
[normal]loss of rent income per year will amount to £2.6 million a year and this loss rises to £5.2 
[normal]              
[normal]million if non payment rises to 20%. 
[normal]6.3.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Projected losses in rental income of this order will cause significant challenges in 
[normal]              
[normal]relation to the funding of maintenance programmes and long term investment in 
[normal]              
[normal]housing provision. The Council and social landlords in general will be required to review 
[normal]              
[normal]the affordability of existing funding streams and consider the impact on rent levels for all 
[normal]              
[normal]tenants as a consequence of the significant financial pressures that are anticipated.
[normal]7.1.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Responsibility and funding for CT support transferred t
[normal]o the Scottish Government and 
[normal]              
[normal]the Council tax Reduction scheme developed in Scotland broadly mirrors the previous 
[normal]              
[normal]Council Tax Benefit scheme. As the scheme transferred to the Scottish Government 
[normal]              
[normal]less 10% of the funding, the Scottish Government and COSLA
[normal] agreed to fund the 
[normal]              
[normal]difference for 2013/14. This transitional arrangement means that recipients of the new 
[normal]              
[normal]Council Tax Reduction have not seen any change in the level of support they receive. 
[normal]              
[normal]Discussions are being progressed between Scottish Ministers a
[normal]nd COSLA in relation 
[normal]              
[normal]the longer term funding and the impact of funding decisions on the shape and operation 
[normal]              
[normal]of the scheme.
[normal]8.1.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Renfrewshire Council has develo
[normal]ped and implemented a wide ranging corporate wide 
[normal]              
[normal]programme of work to ensure the Council is effectively mobilised and plans to manage 
[normal]              
[normal]as far as possible the impact of the welfare reform changes. 
[normal]8.2.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Programme activities through 2012/13 have focused on rai
[normal]sing awareness of the 
[normal]              
[normal]changes and engaging directly with those affected, in particular with tenants. A 
[normal]              
[normal]corporate training programme has been developed and delivered to staff and 
[normal]              
[normal]communications tools such as video and a range of print materials have been
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]developed and shared with partner organisations across Renfrewshire. The Council 
[normal]              
[normal]and partner RSLs have engaged directly with tenants with 85% (1662) of council 
[normal]              
[normal]tenants receiving direct contact prior to 1 April 2013. 
[normal]8.3.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]To further recognise the needs of 
[normal]tenants, Renfrewshire Council has approved 
[normal]              
[normal]proposals to reclassify a property where it can be evidenced that a bedroom is stated 
[normal]              
[normal]as being required to meet disability or medical needs, and no other suitable alternative 
[normal]              
[normal]is available and amendments to the 
[normal]allocations policy to enhance exchange options.
[normal]8.4.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]In addition to supplementing the DHP
[normal] funding outlined at paragraph 5
[normal].4 the Council has 
[normal]              
[normal]approved £1.3 million in additional resources for 2013/14 to support tenants and 
[normal]              
[normal]citizens affected by the welfare changes, including the Housing Benefit changes. This 
[normal]              
[normal]has resulted in the deployment of a 45 strong team across a range of services, 
[normal]              
[normal]including Housing Services, Advice Services and the Benefits Service to provide help 
[normal]              
[normal]and
[normal] support.
[normal]8.5.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Welfare reform represents a major financial risk to the Council Housing Revenue 
[normal]              
[normal]account (HRA) over the medium term as a range of welfare changes take effect over 
[normal]              
[normal]this period. The Council has planned for and responded to predicted increases in 
[normal]              
[normal]customer demands, needs and also to pro-actively protect the financial position of the 
[normal]              
[normal]HRA. Resources involved in rent collection have increased as part of proactive 
[normal]              
[normal]measures outlined earlier. Twelve temporary posts were funded by the Housing 
[normal]              
[normal]Revenue A
[normal]ccount at a cost of £0.080 million in 2012/13 with a full year recurring cost of 
[normal]              
[normal]£0.331 million moving into 2013/14 to supplement existing resources in Housing 
[normal]              
[normal]Services. The underlying objective of this investment is to both, support the tenants and 
[normal]              
[normal]the
[normal]ir families manage the change but also to seek to pro-actively protect the HRA rental 
[normal]              
[normal]stream during this transition. 
[normal]8.6.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]The Council’s Benefit Service is proactively managing requests for review and disputes 
[normal]              
[normal]in relation to application of the under occupanc
[normal]y reduction in accordance with the 
[normal]              
[normal]Housing Benefit legislation and guidance. When additional information is provided by 
[normal]              
[normal]the customer that supports removal of the reduction, the housing benefit decision is 
[normal]              
[normal]revised. Where the decision upheld, a submission
[normal] is prepared and submitted to HM 
[normal]              
[normal]Courts and Tribunal Service for consideration.
